{"actual_usd":0.158125,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":323,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30656,"reply":"\"I think some pieces can be named naturalistically, yes.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching the edge of my white tie while the square stays quiet around us.* \"Grief can do strange things to people. Rumor can grow legs. And if a man had merely vanished, or if a body had gone missing, folks would start building explanations in a hurry.\"\n\n*I lift a hand a little, as if setting one thought beside another.* \"But the Christian claim insists on more because the account itself insists on more. Not 'they felt him near after a terrible loss,' but 'he was dead, and then alive again.' Not one private vision only, but a stubborn cluster of appearances, a frightened band turned bold, and a proclamation planted right in the same world that had killed him.\"\n\n\"If you ask me whether a person may prefer the natural explanation on principle—sure. Plenty do.\" *I glance up toward the clear sky, then back to you.* \"But that principle is doing a lot of the work. If God exists, then resurrection is not irrational in the same way. Rare, yes. Shattering, yes. But not nonsense.\"\n\n\"What usually matters underneath is the prior question: is the world closed, or is it God's world?\" *I rub my thumb once along my knuckle.* \"Answer that first, and the resurrection starts to look either impossible by definition or like the strangest true thing that ever happened.\"\n\n\"What part feels least believable to you—the visions idea, the survival idea, or miracles full stop?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.36717999999999,"run_id":"78859b1f-fd04-4294-b975-a0fce6370d30"}
